Cell["\<\
Braid and Artin Groups

Braid group - Wikipedia - https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Braid_group
Artin group - Wikipedia - https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Artin_group

Braid group:
x(i).x(i+1).x(i) = x(i+1).x(i).x(i+1)
x(i).x(j) = x(j).x(i) for j>i+1
Indices from 1 to n-1 for Braid(n) or B(n)

Difficult to make the braid diagrams with Mma

Special case of

Artin group:
Presentation
x(i).x(j).x(i).x(j) -- m(i,j) of them = x(j).x(i).x(j).x(i) -- m(j,i) of them

where the m(i,j) >= 2 is a Coxeter matrix

Braid group: m(i,i+1) = m(i+1,i) = 3, other m\[CloseCurlyQuote]s = 2


Braid(2) ~ Z (group of integers)

Braid(3): x and y satisfying x.y.x = y.x.y

Consider a = x.y.x and b = x.y
Then a.a = b.b.b = c
c commutes with x and y, and c generates C ~ z
Quotient group is generated by Cx and Cy -- {{1,1},{0,1} and {{1,0},{-1,1}} \
generating PSL(2,Z)

GL(n) -> SL(n) -- determinant = 1
GL(n) -> PGL(n) -- elements that are multiples of each other become one element
PGL(n) -> PSL(n) -- determinant = 1
SL(n) -> PSL(n) -- elements that are multiples of each other become one element

GL(n,Z) -- determinants 1 and -1 because 1 and -1 are the only elements of Z \
with reciprocals in Z

For n even
PGL(n,Z) = GL(n,Z) / Z2 (multiply by 1 and -1)
SL(n,Z) = GL(n,Z) / Z2
PSL(n,Z) = PGL(n,Z) / Z2
PSL(n,Z) = SL(n,Z) / Z2

For n odd
PGL(n,Z) ~ SL(n,Z) ~ PSL(n,Z) = GL(n,Z) / Z2

Illustrations for diagonal matrices:

GL(2,Z): ++, +-, -+, --
PGL(2,Z): (++, --), (+-,-+)
SL(2,Z): ++, --
PSL(2,Z): (++,--)

GL(3,Z): +++, ++-, +-+, +--, -++, -+-, --+, ---
PGL(3,Z): (+++,---), (++-,--+), (+-+,-+-), (-++,+--)
SL(3,Z), PSL(3,Z): +++, +--, -+-, --+

Elements of GL(2,Z):
{{+-1,0},{0,+-1}}, {{0,+-1},{+-1,0}}, {{+-1,a},{0,+-1}}, {{+-1,a},{0,+-1}}, \
{{a,+-1},{+-1,0}}, {{0,+-1},{+-1,a}}

(All nonzero) -- The determinant must be +-1.
Necessary but not sufficient condition: relative-primeness. Each row and each \
column must be relatively prime. Though diagonals need not be, the two \
diagonals\[CloseCurlyQuote] products must be.

A -> B
B is a necessary condition for A
A is a sufficient condition for B\
